name: Eternally
comments: aka  "Eternally (Terry's Theme)" or just often mistakenly called "Limelight".  "The Terry Theme" was the main theme music written by Charlie Chaplin for his 1952 movie, "Limelight".  It became so popular that Englishmen Geoff Parsons and John Turner quickly added lyrics and the new song was christened "Eternally" (and it is now known as the Theme from "Limelight" even though it wasn't actually in the movie).

name: When Not Being Stupid Is Not Enough
李香蘭
comments: Cantonese. Li Xianglan (aka Yoshiko Ōtaka, Yoshiko Yamaguchi, Shirley Yamaguchi) was a Chinese-Japanese actress and singer. In the 1940's, she was forced to hide her mixed heritage and starred in many Japanese propaganda films. The lyrics (about a failed relationship) are not biographical, yet they probably hint at the fact that the singer (or his ex-lover) was forced to hide his own self and feelings.

comments: Oh, the gentlemen are talking and the midnight moon is on the riverside They're drinking up and walking and it is time for me to slide I live in another world where life and death are memorized Where the earth is strung with lover's pearls and all I see are dark eyes. A cock is crowing far away and another soldier's deep in prayer Some mother's child has gone astray, she can't find him anywhere But I hear another rum beating for the dead that rise Whom nature's beast fear as they come and all I see are dark eyes. They tell me to be discreet for all intended purposes They tell me revenge is sweet, I'm sure it is But I feel nothing for their game, where beauty goes unrecognized All I feel is heat and flame, and all I see are dark eyes. Oh, the French girl, she's in paradise and a drunken man is at the wheel Hunger pays a heavy prize to the falling god of speed and steel Oh, time is short and the days are sweet and passion rules the arrow that flies A million faces at my feet but all I see are dark eyes.

name: She Moved Through the Fair
published_by: Emi Film And Theatre Music Ltd[PRS]
comments: This song was collected by Irish poet Padraic Colum and musicologist Herbert Hughes.  The 1909 date represents its first known publication in Hughes' "Irish Country Songs".   It is uncertain the extent to which traditional lyrics for the song were rewritten by Colum.  The Colum version is shorter than many other known versions, and his contribution to the lyrics of the 1909 version seems to be principally editing.  Some scholars assert the song actually dates back to Medieval times. The singer meets his love.  She tells him it "won't be long until our wedding day".  (Longer variants of this song are often entitled "Our Wedding Day".)  The young lady than "moves through the fair".  Most frequently, the girl's ghost returns at the end to again move through the fair. This song is 861 in the Roud Folk Index.

name: Sweet and Lovely
comments: Credits as registered with ASCAP.  In fact, Arnheim, for who this work became a theme song for his orchestra, was not a composer and probably was not involved in the song's composition.  Harry Tobias was a lyricist -- not a composer -- and it is probable that he wrote the song's lyrics.  Neil Moret is a pseudonym used by Chales N. Daniels, who is the probable exclusive composer of the music for the song.
